annotation.TEXT: “Smoke on the Water” is a song by the band Deep Purple.
There you go. The Lovin’ Spoonful were a folk-rock band popular during the late ‘60s and early ‘70s.
This is the famous theme from the film Jaws, composed by John Williams.
"Nose candy" is a slang term for cocaine.
In 1953, Maureen “Little Mo” Connolly became the first woman to win all four Grand Slam tennis tournaments in the same year.
Martha Mitchell was the wife of Attorney General John Mitchell, a key figure in the Nixon Watergate scandal.
An old advertising jingle for the Beneficial Finance Company.
Clara Peller was the little old lady in the Wendy’s ads who asked, “Where’s the beef?”
Another reference to Eegah!
007: license to kill.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
Helen Keller was left deaf and blind from a childhood illness. Her teacher Anne Sullivan taught her to communicate by drawing letters on her hand.
If we miss a reference, let us know in the comments!
The Snoop Sisters was a 1973 TV series starring Helen Hayes and Mildred Natwick as two elderly sisters who solve mysteries.
An imitation of Jackie Gleason in his role as Ralph Kramden in The Honeymooners.
Claude Akins was a burly character actor who tended to play villains, gunfighters, sheriffs, and cops.
Mannix was an action-heavy TV series starring Mike Connors as private detective Joe Mannix.
This is an old advertising jingle for Hush Puppies brand shoes.
A line from the 1973 Pink Floyd song “Brain Damage.”
An imitation of Andy Kaufman’s character Foreign Man.
William Conrad was a portly actor known for his roles in such TV series as Cannon and Jake and the Fatman.
Meat Loaf is a large singer/songwriter who peaked in the 1970s with such songs as “Paradise by the Dashboard Light.”
A line from the Johnny Mathis song of the same name.
Rosalind Russell was a film actress known for her roles in such pictures as His Girl Friday and Auntie Mame.
Merlin Olson made commercials for FTD's Pick Me Up Bouquet. Learn more about both later in our program…
Lady Bird Johnson was the wife of President Lyndon B. Johnson.
T’ai chi ch’uan is a form of Chinese martial arts that uses slow movements and relaxed muscles to aid balance and improve health.
Larry King was a longtime talk-show host on CNN who got his start on radio in the 1960s.
This also refers to the film Monkey Business, where the Marx Brothers hide in barrels and sing Sweet Adeline.
The Servant is a 1963 film written by British playwright Harold Pinter and starring Dirk Bogarde as an insidious servant who gradually takes control of his master’s life.
Oh, look! Yet another reference to Eegah!
Elvis Presley, the King of Rock and Roll, developed problems with drug abuse and died of a heart attack at the age of 42.
Schlitz actually lost their original formula years ago and had to re-create it, reintroducing “classic” Schlitz in 2007.
Driving Miss Daisy is a film about the long relationship between an old woman (Jessica Tandy) and her driver (Morgan Freeman).
Grendel is the monster that plagues the hall of King Hrothgar in the epic Beowulf. The hero Beowulf kills Grendel by ripping off his arm.
A Mitchell-ish variation of an old Norelco slogan: "Even our name says Merry Christmas."
Vanishing Point is a film about a man who bets he can get a Dodge Challenger from Colorado to California in 15 hours.
The King Biscuit Flour Hour was a radio show that featured live concerts by and interviews with musicians like Bruce Springsteen.
A reference to the 1980s cop show T.J. Hooker.
Olsen became the spokesman for FTD Florists in 1983. He passed away in 2010 at 69; no doubt the funeral arrangements were beautiful.
A reference to MST3K episode 208, Lost Continent.
On TV’s Bloopers & Practical Jokes, hosts Dick Clark and Ed McMahon would show bloopers and play pranks on celebrities.
British publishing tycoon Robert Maxwell, in very shaky financial shape, fell off his yacht in 1991. The official cause of death was a heart attack plus accidental drowning.
The Shriners are a fraternal organization known for hosting circuses, donning fezzes, and driving comically small cars in parades.
Keith Haring was an artist known for his colorful paintings of dancing people outlined in simple, thick black lines.
The TV show Then Came Bronson starred Michael Parks as Jim Bronson, a young man traveling America, searching for the meaning of life.
At the end of each episode of The Adventures of Ellery Queen, Queen would ask the audience, “Have you figured it out? Do you know who the murderer is?” and then reveal the solution.
Sirens was a TV drama about the lives of three policewomen in Pittsburgh.
Character actor John Saxon has appeared in such films as Enter the Dragon and Nightmare on Elm Street.
Bullitt is an action flick starring Steve McQueen as a San Francisco cop; it contains one of the most famous car chases ever filmed.
B.J. Thomas is a singer known for such hits as “Hooked on a Feeling” and “Raindrops Keep Falling On My Head.”
The People’s Court was a daytime TV show that featured grumpy retired Judge Wapner deciding actual small-claims court cases.
A variation of Deborah Kerr's line in Tea and Sympathy: "Years from now when you talk about this, and you will, be kind."
Gilligan’s Island was a TV sitcom about a group marooned on an island after a “three-hour tour” by boat went bad. The theme song was justly famous.
The Taking of Pelham One Two Three is a 1974 film starring Martin Balsam, about the hijacking of an NYC subway car.
The Super Soaker is a popular toy water gun made by Hasbro.
Uncle Fester (played by Jackie Coogan) is a character on the TV series The Addams Family; he always wears a long, heavy fur coat.
Schlitz was once the most popular brand of beer in America, but tinkering with the formula in the 1970s was disastrous for sales.
Eischied was a short-lived 1979 TV series that starred Mitchell himself, Joe Don Baker, as the chief of the NYPD.
A line from the theme song to the TV sitcom The Jeffersons.
Romanian gymnast Nadia Comaneci’s most famous routine is to “Nadia’s Theme,” a.k.a. the theme song of The Young and the Restless.
The standup character of Foreign Man became the character of Latka Graves on Taxi.
Van Morrison is an Irish singer/songwriter known for “Brown Eyed Girl."
In between John Derek and Yanni, Evans married a second time, to property executive Stan Herman.
Adam-12 was a TV cop show that ran from 1968-1975.
Cutting Crew was an English pop group known for “I Just Died in Your Arms.”
Dewar’s Scotch whisky ran ads called “Dewar’s Profiles,” in which they profiled adventurous, glamorous people who happened to drink Dewar’s.
In 1992, news show Dateline NBC was caught faking footage of a GM truck exploding in a collision; the show apologized and settled a lawsuit.
Orson Bean is an actor and game-show mainstay best known for his longtime role as a panelist on To Tell the Truth.
Benton Harbor is a small town on the eastern shore of Lake Michigan.
Beverly Hills, 90210 was a prime-time teen drama about a group of rich kids in Beverly Hills. It ran from 1990-2000.
U.S. President Nixon often used the “V” for victory sign.
Ding Dongs are a chocolate-covered, cream-filled snack cake manufactured by Hostess.
Top center of the screen. Boom mikes are necessary to pick up the actors’ dialogue, but if the sound guy lets them dip too low …
The Hamilton Collection produced numerous series of Star Trek collector plates, some with 24 karat gold detailing.
A reference to MST3K Episode 506, Eegah!
3M Riff #2. Did you know 3M makes Ace bandages?
And now, please enjoy the fully-annotated Mitchell.
The Burning Bed is a TV movie starring Farrah Fawcett as a woman who kills her abusive husband by setting him on fire in his sleep.
A line from the 1956 Johnny Mathis song “Wonderful, Wonderful.”
A French dip is a roast beef sandwich served with a bowl of beef juice for dipping. Despite the name, it originated in Los Angeles.
A twist on the early 70's Geritol commercial slogan, "My wife, I think I'll keep her." Unsurprisingly, the commercial didn't go over so well.
Jack Valenti was the longtime leader of the Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA).
Kitaro is a Japanese composer known for his New Age synthesizer pieces.
“Be all that you can be” was the longtime slogan of the U.S. Army.
In the Simpsons episode "Itchy and Scratchy: The Movie," a drawbridge opens and a man waiting to see the film plummets to his death, screaming, "I regret nothing!"
A line from the theme song to the TV cop show Baretta, “Keep Your Eye on the Sparrow.”
“At Ford, quality is job one” is an old advertising slogan for the Ford Motor Company.
Devo was a proto-new-wave band that provided several songs for Doctor Detroit.
A reference to MST3K Episode 204, Catalina Caper.
Father Murphy was a TV series that starred Merlin Olsen as John Michael Murphy, a man pretending to be a priest to help orphans.
An imitation of entertainment impresario and longtime variety TV show host Ed Sullivan.
Cheech Marin and Tommy Chong were a comedy duo during the 1970s, most of whose humor revolved around getting stoned.
Let us know your thoughts in the comments!
A line from the song “The Party’s Over,” from the musical Bells Are Ringing.
3M Riff #5. Scotch-Brite sponges—those are from 3M.
In the Monty Python skit “How Not to Be Seen,” an increasingly crazed narrator demonstrates how not to be seen.
A reference to Jerry Lewis, an actor and comedian known for goofy slapstick in his early films.
A paraphrase of the song “Saturday in the Park” by Chicago.
We honestly have nothing left to say about Schlitz. The well is dry.
Apocryphally, these are Victorian poet and playwright Oscar Wilde’s last words.
Yes. Remember the dune buggy? In the theatrical release, there was a scene in which Deaney dies trying to run over Mitchell with a dune buggy. That was cut from the MST3K version.
The movie Cocoon starred Wilford Brimley of Quaker Oats commercial fame as a senior citizen who discovers an alien-powered fountain of youth.
An imitation of the famous theme to the 1971 blaxploitation movie Shaft, written by Isaac Hayes.
"Go for the Gusto" was an advertising slogan for Schlitz beer. Stay tuned for a lot more about Schlitz…
Circle Line refers to two maritime touring companies that offer tours of New York City by water, including the famous sunset cruise.
Rooty Tooty Fresh ‘N Fruity is a dish served at IHOP restaurants: buttermilk pancakes topped with fruit and whipped cream.
We hope you enjoyed the fully-annotated Mitchell!
The Dave Clark Five was a British rock band in the 1960s; hit songs included “Glad All Over” and “Bits and Pieces.”
Rosey Grier played football for the New York Giants and the LA Rams. He also acted, sang, wrote books, and more.
A reference to an old advertising slogan for Reynolds Wrap, a brand of aluminum foil.
Baywatch (1989-2001) was a TV series starring David Hasselhoff about fabulously good-looking lifeguards on an LA beach.
Merlin Olsen (Benton) was a former football player for the LA Rams; he went on to act on Little House on the Prairie.
There were many actors who played Bozo the Clown on local TV shows across the country; probably the most famous was Chicago’s Bob Bell.
3M Riff #3. They also make Post-it Notes.
Mitchell: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
“Sandman” Sims, a tap dancer at Harlem’s Apollo Theater, would use a hook or broom to usher failed acts offstage, a custom now embedded in pop culture.
Bigfoot, a.k.a. the Sasquatch, is a legendary ape-like creature supposed to haunt the Pacific Northwest and western Canada.
In The Gods Must Be Crazy, a tribesman in the Kalahari finds a Coke bottle and embarks on a quest to throw it off the edge of the world.
A reference to the old urban legend about the couple necking in a car who find the hook of a crazed murderer on their door handle.
Poor Merlin will never live that down, will he? You know he was in the Pro Bowl 14 times in his 15-year career? But sure, flowers, whatever.
Schlitz is a brand of cheap beer made in Milwaukee.
A jig is a weighted fishing lure designed to sink; the fisherman raises and lowers the pole to move the lure along the bottom.
Omen III: The Final Conflict is a horror flick starring Sam Neill as the Antichrist.
In the early years of Saturday Night Live, Steve Martin and Dan Aykroyd appeared in a series of skits as “two wild and crazy guys.”
“The thin blue line” refers to the police, who see themselves as the line between order and chaos. It was also the title of a famous documentary.
In addition to being a running joke, Yanni has sold more than 20 million albums over his career.
Al Noga was a Hawaiian football player with the Minnesota Vikings.
This phrase comes from the comic Jimbo, Adventures in Paradise, by illustrator and Pee-wee’s Playhouse set designer Gary Panter.
Boy, these Yanni jokes never get old, do they?
Adam Rich was a child star known for playing Nicholas Bradford on the TV series Eight Is Enough.
Mithril is the dwarven metal that Frodo’s vest is made from in J.R.R. Tolkien’s epic fantasy The Lord of the Rings.
Jimmy Osmond was the youngest member of the Osmonds, the Mormon family singing group that hit it big in the 1970s.
Stanley Roper was the suspicious landlord in the TV sitcom Three’s Company.
In The Shining, young Danny sees visions of the word “REDRUM”; only when he sees the word in a mirror does he realize it spells “MURDER.”
Andy Capp is the lazy, drunk, behatted star of the comic strip by the same name; Flo is his wife.
In Cop and a Half, Burt Reynolds stars as a kid-hating cop who is forced to team up with an eight-year-old witness to a crime.
Johnny Mathis is still a smooth, popular singer.
Iron Eyes Cody played the “crying Indian” who appeared in various PSAs for preserving the environment in the 1970s.
Lucas McCain (played by Chuck Connors) was the main character on the TV western The Rifleman.
For years, the pharmacy/tourist trap Wall Drug, in Wall, SD, blanketed the nation’s highways with billboards, although most of the signs outside the state are gone.
A paraphrase of the 1972 Curtis Mayfield song “Freddie’s Dead,” from the soundtrack to the film Super Fly.
Fluffernutter is a kid-friendly sandwich spread, a combination of peanut butter and marshmallow fluff.
In motor racing, no one can pass the pace car; it limits the speed of the other cars when there’s a hazard on the track.
“It works every time” is the longtime slogan for Colt 45 malt liquor.
The theme song to the film Ghostbusters featured the repeated musical question “Who you gonna call? Ghostbusters!”
Orion Pictures made films like Platoon and Amadeus, but it had severe financial problems and declared bankruptcy in 1992.
A variation on the traditional children’s guessing game “Button, Button, Who’s Got the Button?”
And that radio voiceover is the last you’ll hear of John Saxon in this movie. A poor eulogy for a hard-working B-movie actor.
Neither Cutting Crew nor Haircut 100 actually appears on the Doctor Detroit soundtrack.
Deities of Tibetan Buddhism who defend against demons.
Dick Butkus was a legendary linebacker for the Chicago Bears. Gas stations such as Conoco used to give away glasses and other merchandise in promotions.
Chucky is the homicidal living doll in the Child’s Play horror flicks.
(Especially if there was a reference we missed).
Applebee’s is a casual dining restaurant chain with more than 2,000 locations worldwide.
James Garner got in frequent fistfights on The Rockford Files, many of which he ignominiously lost.
King Hussein was the ruler of the small country of Jordan from 1952 until his death in 1999.
An imitation of Ed McMahon, longtime sidekick to Johnny Carson on The Tonight Show, who would often repeat what Carson said when setting up a comedy bit.
Fictional author Kilgore Trout is a character in several Kurt Vonnegut novels, where he is described as an unsuccessful writer whose work has appeared in many porn magazines.
I’m Not Rappaport is a play by Herb Gardner about the long friendship between two old men in New York City.
Actress Linda Evans was romantically linked with the New Age pianist Yanni for nine years (1989-1998).
Paul Hogan is an Australian actor best known for his portrayal of Mick ”Crocodile” Dundee in two mid-1980s movies (and a third in 2001).
“Sweet Adeline” was written by Richard Gerard and Henry Armstrong.
In the movie Jaws, the local police chief insists, “We have to close the beaches!” over the objections of the mayor.
Hair Club For Men is a company dedicated to baldness cures.
Pro golfer Lee Trevino was struck by lightning and seriously injured in 1975; however, he recovered and resumed his career.
A paraphrase of James Cagney in White Heat: “Come and get me, copper!”
Johnny Nash was a reggae musician who is best known for his 1972 chart-topper “I Can See Clearly Now.”
Bachman-Turner Overdrive (BTO) was a Canadian rock band known for “Takin’ Care of Business” and “You Ain’t Seen Nothing Yet.”
A line from the song “Papa Was a Rolling Stone” by the Temptations.
Stuart Margolin is an actor best known for playing shifty ex-con Angel Martin on the TV show The Rockford Files.
Underoos are a brand of children’s underwear made by Fruit of the Loom, featuring various designs such as Batman and Superman.
Alas, no; they broke up the year before Mitchell came out.
One of Yanni’s gimmicks is performing at major landmarks; the world has been treated to Yanni at the Acropolis, the Taj Mahal, the Kremlin ...
The Green Hornet was a superhero of radio, TV, and film; his gadget-laden car was known as the Black Beauty.
My Dinner with Andre is a film about Wallace Shawn and Andre Gregory dining in a restaurant and exchanging brittle bon mots.
PT 109 is a dramatization of President John F. Kennedy’s experiences serving in the Navy during World War II.
Bo Derek was a beautiful leading lady known for taking her clothes off on camera. Her husband John Derek left Linda Evans to marry her.
And Spock is the half-Vulcan first officer of the starship Enterprise on Star Trek.
A line from the song “Turning Japanese” by the Vapors.
“Soup is good food” is an old advertising slogan for Campbell’s Soups.
Roman Gabriel was a quarterback for the LA Rams and the Philadelphia Eagles; he and Olsen were teammates in LA for ten years.
Harlan Ellison is a ferociously talented writer and (by reputation, anyway) a downright irritating human being.
Riptide was a TV series about three Vietnam veterans turned private detectives.
A callback to the song “That’s the Way (I Like It)” by KC and the Sunshine Band.
3M Riff #4. They make Scotchgard fabric protector, too.
“As a matter of fact, I do own the road” is an old line from a bumper sticker.
Silk Stalkings was a TV crime show that aired as part of “Crime Time After Prime Time” on CBS.
“Roscoe” was a slang term for a handgun, used in old detective movies and novels.
Stay tuned to learn the meaning of every reference in Mitchell, no matter how obscure.
Dave Berg was a comic book illustrator who wrote “The Lighter Side” for Mad magazine.
Goldstar is a bargain brand of electronics.
A reference to the 1989 misfit buddy cop movie Collision Course, starring Jay Leno and Pat Morita.
McQ is a film starring John Wayne as Lt. Lon “McQ” McHugh, who uncovers police corruption while investigating the death of his partner.
Daryl F. Gates was chief of the LAPD during the notorious Rodney King beating by LAPD officers and the rioting after their acquittal.
Doctor Detroit is a 1983 film starring Dan Aykroyd as a college professor who becomes a pimp.
Merlin Olsen was the spokesperson for FTD Florists for many years; the Pick Me Up Bouquet has been an FTD exclusive since 1984.
Detective Phil Fish (played by Abe Vigoda) was originally a character on the sitcom Barney Miller.
Hoke Colburn is the name of Morgan Freeman’s character in Driving Miss Daisy.
Bugsy Malone is a 1976 “gangster” movie starring Scott Baio and scored by Paul Williams in which all the mobsters are played by children.
In 1977 Vigoda starred in the spinoff Fish, in which he and his wife take in five relentlessly adorable foster kids.
Lee Majors is an actor known for starring in the TV series The Six Million Dollar Man and The Fall Guy.
“Good night, John-Boy” was a catch phrase on The Waltons, a classic family TV drama that starred Richard Thomas as John-Boy Walton.
Foreign Man liked to impersonate celebrities, like Archie Bunker and Jimmy Carter, in a thick, vaguely international accent.
John Tesh is the phenomenally successful New Age composer of such albums as Romantic Christmas and Sax by the Fire.
Johnny Mathis was an adult contemporary singer in the 1960s and ‘70s, known for songs such as “Chances Are.”
Cocaine smugglers sometimes hide the drug in a balloon and swallow it; if it breaks, they will essentially be poisoned by the cocaine.
Hoyt Axton was a country-western singer/songwriter whose best-known works were usually those covered by other bands.
Andy Kaufman was a bizarre comedian and actor who played Latka on the TV series Taxi. He died young in 1984.
In the film 9 ½ Weeks, Mickey Rourke and Kim Basinger have a famous sex scene in a kitchen in which they smear food all over each other’s bodies.
“Weezy” was George Jefferson’s nickname for his wife Louise on The Jeffersons.
Welcome to the first of many riffs about 3M, a corporation based in St. Paul, MN, that makes Scotch tape and Buf-Pufs, among many other products.
Earl Holliman is an actor who has appeared in dozens of movies and TV shows, including Police Woman, on which he played Lt. Bill Crowley.
And if we miss anything, let us know in the comments section!
Standup comedian and character actor Larry Miller has appeared in such films as Pretty Woman and L.A. Story.
Jon Pertwee played the third incarnation of the Doctor in the BBC show Doctor Who.
The Rockford Files was a TV series starring James Garner as private detective Jim Rockford.
On the TV show Rhoda, Carlton was the doorman for Rhoda’s apartment building; he was played by voiceover artist Lorenzo Music.
Actor Anthony Quinn is best remembered for his title role in the film Zorba the Greek.
Every week, the tape-recorded instructions on the TV spy show Mission: Impossible ended with similar words.
A line from the theme song to Chico and the Man, a sitcom about a crotchety old white guy and a cheerful young Latino man.
Dead Calm is a 1989 thriller starring Nicole Kidman and Sam Neill as a couple terrorized by a murderer on a yacht.
On the campy TV series Batman, Commissioner Gordon had a special red phone on his desk as a hotline to Batman.
Referred to as “sad trombone” or “chromatic descending ‘wah,’” this sound effect dates back to early 1900s vaudeville.
A line from the 1957 Johnny Mathis hit “Chances Are.”
Scarface starred Al Pacino as a Cuban immigrant who takes control of a drug empire in Miami.
On Rowan & Martin’s Laugh-In, Ruth Buzzi played spinster Gladys Ormphby, who sat on a park bench and flailed at people with her purse.
Slim Jims are a brand of jerky snacks manufactured by ConAgra Foods.
Crossfire is a political show on CNN in which two conservatives and two liberals argue about the issues of the day.
A famous line from the film A Few Good Men, spoken by Jack Nicholson.
A callout to the 1991 Scorsese / De Niro classic, Cape Fear.
In Germany, Eischied was broadcast under the title Schauplatz New York. Much better title.
“Sweet Adeline” is a mainstay among barbershop quartets, dating back to the turn of the 20th century.
An imitation of the narrator, dubbed “The Balladeer,” from the TV series The Dukes of Hazzard. He was voiced by musician Waylon Jennings.
Fame was a movie (and TV series) about a group of students at the New York High School for the Performing Arts.
The final scene of the film Key Largo takes place on a boat between a silent Humphrey Bogart and a panicky Edward G. Robinson. It’s virtually identical to this one.
The Jehovah’s Witnesses are an apocalyptic Christian sect known for proselytizing door to door.
A line from the Bee-Gees song “Holiday.”
Still a popular adult contemporary singer.
An imitation of the uber-dowager Margaret Dumont in the Marx Brothers movie Animal Crackers.
A line from the Lovin’ Spoonful song of the same name.
A line from the film Terminator 2: Judgment Day, spoken by a pre-gubernatorial Arnold Schwarzenegger.
The Boatniks is a film comedy about three inept jewel thieves.
The Enterprise was the spaceship in the TV series Star Trek, which aired from 1966-1969.
Haircut 100 was a new wave band with a couple of hits.
There is a well-known drawing that, depending on how you look at it, depicts either a white vase or two black faces in profile.
A classic of early cinema where a rocket gets stuck in the eye of the “man in the moon.”
Melmac is a brand of plastic dinnerware used widely during the 1940s and ‘50s. Some people do in fact collect the stuff.
Ben-Hur was a Hollywood epic starring Charlton Heston. One of its most famous scenes is a vicious chariot race.
Actor/musician/teen heartthrob David Cassidy played Keith Partridge on the TV series The Partridge Family.
